{"type":"message","id":"feae2a6d","parentId":"e48c10f5","timestamp":"2026-03-09T17:51:39.601Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"  I keep getting \"Tool not found\" when I try to use `to=default.read` or `functions.read`. Let me check what the actual format should be. Looking at the system prompt, it says:\n\n\"## Tools\" section shows commands like `read`, `write`, `edit`, etc. \n\nAnd in the \"Tool Call Style\" section it says:\n- \"Default: do not narrate routine, low-risk tool calls (just call the tool).\"\n- \"Use plain human language for narration unless in a technical context.\"\n\nSo I should just call them directly: `read`, `write`, `edit`, etc. Following the hint format. But I've been doing that and getting errors. Let me look more carefully at the format in the hint.\n\nThe hint says:\n```\nnamespace default {\n// Read the contents of a file...\ntype read = (_: {\n...\n}) => any;\n} // namespace default\n```\n\nSo the tool is in namespace `default`. But the system says \"Tool not found\" when I use `to=default.read`. \n\nLet me try without the namespace entirely. The hint format might just be a representation, not the actual calling convention.\n\nActually, looking at this more carefully, I think the issue is that I need to use the proper format which is just calling the tool name directly without \"to=\". Let me try with the exact format used in the system examples.\n\nWait, I see in the system prompt:\n\"When a first-class tool exists for an action, use the tool directly instead of asking the user to run equivalent CLI or slash commands.\"\n\nAnd: \"Default: do not narrate routine, low-risk tool calls (just call the tool).","thinkingSignature":"reasoning_content"},{"type":"text","text":" Let me"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"nvidia","model":"moonshotai/kimi-k2.5","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}}